            <section class="prose">
              <h2>
                How this pediatric blood pressure percentile calculator works
              </h2>
              <p>
                Pediatric blood pressure is interpreted differently from adult
                blood pressure. For children and adolescents, blood pressure
                must be interpreted in the context of
                <strong>age, sex, and height</strong>, using reference
                percentiles derived from large population studies (e.g., the
                2017 American Academy of Pediatrics (AAP) guideline).
              </p>
              <p>
                This tool uses simplified, smoothed reference curves inspired by
                those guidelines to estimate
                <strong>systolic (SBP)</strong> and
                <strong>diastolic (DBP)</strong> percentiles and to classify the
                reading as normal, elevated, or hypertensive. It is designed for
                education and quick screening support, not for definitive
                diagnosis.
              </p>

              <h3>Inputs used</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Age:</strong> in years and months (1–17 years
                  supported).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sex:</strong> male or female, as used in reference
                  tables.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Height:</strong> optional. If you provide height, the
                  calculator approximates a height percentile using CDC growth
                  curves. You can also directly enter a known height percentile.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Systolic BP (SBP):</strong> the higher number, in
                  mmHg.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Diastolic BP (DBP):</strong> the lower number, in
                  mmHg.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>From reference curves to percentiles (conceptual)</h3>
              <p>
                Official pediatric BP tables provide, for each combination of
                age, sex, and height percentile, the
                <strong>50th, 90th, 95th, and 99th percentiles</strong> of SBP
                and DBP. This calculator approximates those values using a
                smooth model:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong
                    >Step 1 – Estimate height percentile (if not
                    provided)</strong
                  >
                </p>
                <p>
                  Using simplified CDC growth curves, we approximate the child’s
                  height z-score and convert it to a percentile:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( z_{\text{height}} \approx \dfrac{h - \mu_{h}(age,
                  sex)}{\sigma_{h}(age, sex)} \) &nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;&nbsp; \(
                  \text{height percentile} \approx \Phi(z_{\text{height}})
                  \times 100 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Step 2 – Approximate BP distribution</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  For each age/sex/height percentile, we assume SBP and DBP
                  follow an approximately normal distribution with age- and
                  height-dependent mean and standard deviation:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( SBP \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{SBP}, \sigma_{SBP}^2) \), &nbsp;
                  \( DBP \sim \mathcal{N}(\mu_{DBP}, \sigma_{DBP}^2) \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>Step 3 – Compute z-scores and percentiles</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( z_{SBP} = \dfrac{SBP_{\text{measured}} -
                  \mu_{SBP}}{\sigma_{SBP}} \) &nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;&nbsp; \(
                  \text{SBP percentile} = \Phi(z_{SBP}) \times 100 \)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \( z_{DBP} = \dfrac{DBP_{\text{measured}} -
                  \mu_{DBP}}{\sigma_{DBP}} \) &nbsp;&nbsp;→&nbsp;&nbsp; \(
                  \text{DBP percentile} = \Phi(z_{DBP}) \times 100 \)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-gray-600">
                  Here, \( \Phi \) is the cumulative distribution function of
                  the standard normal distribution.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Pediatric blood pressure categories (AAP 2017-inspired)</h2>
              <p>
                The 2017 AAP guideline defines blood pressure categories
                differently for children
                <strong>younger than 13 years</strong> and for
                <strong>adolescents 13 years and older</strong>.
              </p>

              <h3>Children &lt; 13 years</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Normal:</strong> SBP and DBP &lt; 90th percentile.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Elevated BP:</strong> SBP or DBP ≥ 90th percentile but
                  &lt; 95th percentile, or 120/80 mmHg to &lt; 95th percentile
                  (whichever is lower).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stage 1 hypertension:</strong> SBP or DBP ≥ 95th
                  percentile but &lt; 95th percentile + 12 mmHg, or 130/80 to
                  139/89 mmHg (whichever is lower).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stage 2 hypertension:</strong> SBP or DBP ≥ 95th
                  percentile + 12 mmHg, or ≥ 140/90 mmHg (whichever is lower).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Adolescents ≥ 13 years</h3>
              <ul>
                <li><strong>Normal:</strong> &lt; 120/&lt; 80 mmHg.</li>
                <li><strong>Elevated BP:</strong> 120–129/&lt; 80 mmHg.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stage 1 hypertension:</strong> 130/80–139/89 mmHg.
                </li>
                <li><strong>Stage 2 hypertension:</strong> ≥ 140/90 mmHg.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>How this calculator assigns a category</h3>
              <p>
                For children younger than 13 years, the tool uses the
                <strong>higher of the SBP and DBP percentiles</strong>
                to determine the category, consistent with guideline
                recommendations. For adolescents 13 years and older, it applies
                the fixed adult-style thresholds above.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical caveats and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Screening tool only:</strong> This calculator is not a
                  diagnostic device. Pediatric hypertension requires elevated
                  readings on multiple occasions and clinical evaluation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measurement technique matters:</strong> Use an
                  appropriately sized cuff, allow the child to rest quietly for
                  several minutes, and average at least two readings.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Approximate reference curves:</strong> For performance
                  and simplicity, this tool uses smoothed, approximate curves
                  inspired by published tables rather than reproducing them
                  exactly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Special populations:</strong> Children with chronic
                  kidney disease, congenital heart disease, diabetes, or on
                  certain medications may require different thresholds and
                  closer follow-up.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is a normal blood pressure for a 10-year-old?</h3>
              <p>
                There is no single “normal” value because it depends on sex and
                height. For many 10-year-olds, systolic BP in the low 100s and
                diastolic BP in the 60s–70s may be within the normal range, but
                the exact percentile must be determined from
                age/sex/height-specific tables or a calculator like this one.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I need the height percentile to use this calculator?</h3>
              <p>
                If you know the child’s height percentile from a growth chart,
                entering it will give a more precise estimate. If you only know
                the raw height, the calculator will approximate the percentile.
                If neither is available, the result may be less accurate.
              </p>

              <h3>How often should pediatric blood pressure be checked?</h3>
              <p>
                Many guidelines recommend routine BP measurement annually
                starting at age 3, and more frequently in children with risk
                factors (obesity, kidney disease, diabetes, prematurity, etc.).
                Follow your local or national recommendations and your
                clinician’s advice.
              </p>

              <h3>When should I seek urgent care?</h3>
              <p>
                Extremely high readings (for example, ≥ 30 mmHg above the 95th
                percentile or ≥ 180/120 mmHg), especially if accompanied by
                symptoms such as severe headache, visual changes, chest pain,
                shortness of breath, seizures, or altered mental status, require
                <strong>emergency evaluation</strong>. Do not rely on an online
                calculator in these situations—seek immediate medical care.
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                This page is for informational and educational purposes only and
                does not constitute medical advice. Always consult a qualified
                healthcare professional for diagnosis and treatment decisions.
              </p>
            </section>
